Analysis of Algorithms :

Introduction

Analysis of Algorithms is the process of evaluating an algorithm's efficiency in terms of execution time and memory usage.
It helps compare different algorithms and choose the most efficient one for a given problem.

Why Data Structures and Algorithms (DSA)?

Improve program efficiency and performance.
Reduce execution time and memory consumption.
Solve complex problems effectively.
Build scalable and optimized software applications.

Types of Data Structures

Linear Data Structures: Array, Linked List, Stack, Queue.
Non-Linear Data Structures: Tree, Graph, Heap.

Algorithm Analysis

Measures an algorithm's performance regardless of hardware or programming language.
Focuses on Time Complexity and Space Complexity.

Time Complexity

Represents the time required by an algorithm as the input size increases.
Expressed using asymptotic notation.

Space Complexity

Represents the amount of memory used by an algorithm during execution.
Asymptotic Notations
Big O (O): Upper bound (Worst Case).
Omega (Ω): Lower bound (Best Case).
Theta (Θ): Tight bound (Average/Exact Case).

Cases of Algorithm Analysis

Best Case: Minimum execution time for a favorable input.
Average Case: Expected execution time for a typical input.
Worst Case: Maximum execution time for the least favorable input.

Finding Time Complexity

Analyze loops, nested loops, and recursive calls.
Examples:
Single loop → O(n)
Nested loops → O(n²)
Binary Search → O(log n)
Merge Sort → O(n log n)
Recursive algorithms are analyzed using recurrence relations.

Importance

Helps select the most efficient algorithm.
Optimizes software performance.
Reduces resource usage.
Enables scalable and maintainable applications.